    {
      "id": "0fbb91008f09f36c4c52ecaed1606cfc3ca214e5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2021-08-14 21:00:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nplease note parallel configure checks break cached configure runs for everybody that happen to use them (including my builders).\n\nSince cached configure runs are desirable and a feature we carry, either new configure logic needs to accomodate cached runs too or we need to make a decision that we no longer want to have cached configure support (which when enabled works much faster than even parallel configure, of course)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d1b686dd88c1ffb19967aa0b90abdd182f17de36",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-08-15 08:09:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI don't know much about the internals of configure, but is there a way to determine if there is a cache, and if not then run the configure in parallel?  Alternately, enable or disable parallel configure with an option so that the Jenkins builders (which I don't think ever use cache) can run the parallel configure, and Oleg's build can use cache?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
